title: St. Joseph looks like itself in rout of Atlantic City
text:
More coverage: Southeastern Pa. high school sports 
Horne, a 5-foot-10, 180-pound running back, collected 217 yards on 17 carries and scored two touchdowns for the Wildcats, the No. 12 team in The Inquirer Top 25. 
"This was a statement game," Horne said, sitting in a golf cart on the field with ice bags on his left ankle and right knee. "We wanted to let people know that St. Joe's hasn't fallen off. We're still a powerhouse." 
With lopsided losses to division rival St. Augustine Prep in the season opener and to Maryland power Mt. St. Joseph on Oct. 10, St. Joseph has struggled a bit to find its footing this season. 
But the Wildcats looked familiar on a cool, gray afternoon on their home field, controlling the line of scrimmage and unleashing a potent ground game. 
"I liked the way we ran the football," St. Joseph coach Paul Sacco said. 
More than a few St. Joseph fans probably were enthused by the play of several freshmen and sophomores. 
Sophomore Qwashin Townsel, a fullback playing his second game after sitting out the first four as a transfer from Holy Spirit, ran for 124 yards and a touchdown on 17 carries. 
"He's a baby but he's going to be a good one for us," Sacco said of Townsel. 
Freshman DeAndre Kennedy, a star on the ninth-grade team that has been overpowering the competition, scored his first varsity touchdown on a 12-yard run in the fourth quarter, and several other freshmen and sophomores were making plays against a Group 5 opponent. 
"Some of these young kids can really play," Sacco said. 
St. Joseph has won six consecutive state titles and 24 overall, so the Wildcats have as much tradition as any program in South Jersey. 
And the future looks bright based on the presence of several promising underclassmen. 
But for seniors such and Lomax and Horne, as well as Salaam Horne - A'Laam's twin - and several others, the focus is 2015. 
"It's been frustrating because we haven't been at our best," A'Laam Horne said. "But we came together today. We're going to go from here. We still can win a state title." 
Lomax said putting half-a-hundred on the scoreboard against a talented opponent felt like old times - and might have been a preview of times to come as well. 
"This was the type of game we've been used to in the past," Lomax said. "It was St. Joseph football, manhandling teams. 
"I think we're going to build off of this."
